<paragraph blockId="20.[167,779,947,1179]" pageId="20" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,986,1010]" pageId="20" pageNumber="527">Identification.</emphasis>
Perennial tussock grass with conspicuous rhizomes, 
<quantity box="[282,387,1020,1044]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="20" pageNumber="527" unit="m" value="1.1" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.7">0.7–1.5 m</quantity>
height. Identified by its leaf-blades linear-lanceolate, plain or conduplicate, obtuse apex, glabrous to densely covered with hairs, 
<quantity box="[560,665,1088,1112]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="527" unit="cm" value="27.5" valueMax="35.0" valueMin="20.0">20–35 cm</quantity>
long, 0.5– 1.0 cm wide, sometimes presenting a bluish coloration. Inflorescence with 9–25 alternate branches, 
<quantity box="[629,720,1155,1179]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="527" unit="cm" value="15.0" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="5.0">5–25 cm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="527" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[168,778,1195,1535]" pageId="20" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,280,1195,1219]" pageId="20" pageNumber="527">Remarks.</emphasis>
A common species on the native grassland, occurring isolated or in small clusters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[168,778,1195,1535]" pageId="20" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,360,1268,1292]" pageId="20" pageNumber="527">Brazilian range.</emphasis>
Midwest, North (PA and TO states), Northeast (BA, MA and RN states), South (except SC state) and Southeast (except RJ state) regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
